The Tailor RNA-Seq Pipeline: a Tool for De Novo Disease Biomarker Identification

BIOL607 Final Project

Andrew Judell-Halfpenny

Fall Semester 2018

Background

High-Throughput Sequencing is one of the most promising tools available to researchers united by the common-goals of personalized medicine. Identifying a unique transcriptional signature through comparative RNA-Seq analysis provides enables earlier detection, informs future drug design, and ultimately saves lives. The first step towards providing targeted interventions for genetic diseases is identifying the genomic features common to a particular phenotype. . But identifying clinically informative features from the massive sequence libraries (~1-2 Tb) produced during one experiment exceed the capabilities of most personal computers and necessitates the use of a high-performance computing cluster (HPCC) with a standardized downstream analysis procedure. These circumstances create a skills-gap bottleneck that requires molecular biologists to develop new skill sets with extensive knowledge of computer programming and software engineering. This bottleneck is further exacerbated by the difficulty of identifying high-confidence biomarkers for a population from a small sample experiment with low statistical power. The Tailor Pipeline was designed to address these issues and facilitate biomarker discovery from comparative RNA-Seq analyses between two or more conditions.

Introduction to the Tailor Pipeline

The Tailor pipeline was developed to perform comparative genomic analyses designed by UMass Bostons Center for Personalized Cancer Therapy and Genomics Core. Tailor is optimized for use with the binary bcl data files produced by the Sequencing-by-Synthesis (SBS) protocol of an Illumina HiSeq 2500. In less than 72 hours, Tailor can analyze the ~ 1Tb of data produced during a single sequencing run.

The Tailor RNA-Seq analysis pipeline is an end-to-end tool-suite that produces a set of biomarkers from the significant differential expression between two or more conditions. Tailor extends and simplifies the Tophat-Cufflinks tool-suite for RNA-Seq library preparation in order to perform comparative gene expression analyses and visualize significant differences in the gene expression profiles between two or more conditions. The pipeline provides an automated workflow that facilitates resource requests over a high performance computing cluster through multi-step, in-parallel, computational jobs submitted to either LSF or SGE job-schedulers. The output from each previous step is automatically input to the next step which is initiated with a simple two-word command (tailor bcl2fastq, tailor fastqc, tailor trimgalore) from a command-line interface.

To perform Tailors differential expression analysis, the user must provide a sample sheet that maps the names of the input (bcl) files to the human readable names of the samples from each group or condition. Tailor can only quantify expression of annotated gene models that index a sequenced genome. Tailor includes a secondary suite of tools for genome indexing and gene-model building for analyses with non-model organisms. Tailors workflow can be customized via modification of the provided settings configuration file. This feature enables the user to initiate the workflow from any step of the pipeline and utilizing most standard RNA-Seq file formats (fastq.gz, sam, bam, gtf, gff, cxb, and fg.gz). Several pre-configured settings files are included with Tailor to provide different levels of de-novo feature discovery. The default workflow does not perform any novel feature discovery and is the simplest workflow. The genome-guided, de novo workflow uses gene-model annotations to guid isoform discovery. The fully de novo workflow is operated without gene models and is the most computationally intensive.

Research Design

The Tailor pipeline begins with human readable file conversion as well read de-multiplexing via bcl2fastq, software designed by Illumina HiSeq data. The next step in the pipeline is FastQC quality control inspection of the sequence data in order to check for over-represented sequences, anomalous features, and phred quality scores (1). The paired end reads must be parsed by Trim-galore in order to identify the unique adapter sequence that ligated the reads from a particular sample to the bottom of the flow-cell (2). After adapter trimming, the sequence libraries, and can be mapped to the reference genome/transcriptome by Tophat, a splice aware mapper. (3). After read-mapping, the transcripts are and the sequences of the gene models are assembled by Cufflinks into de-Bruijn graphs (4). Cufflinks determines how to assemble the transcripts and the gene structure Bipartite matching isoforms into minimum-spanning-trees (mst) that account for the distribution of reads from a gene. After the transcripts of each sample are assembled into a gene transfer format file, they are compared to the reference annotation by Cuffmerge (5). The new gene models and the mapped bam files from the Tophat step are input to Cuffquant for gene expression quantification (6). The gene models and the gene expression files are input to Cuffdiff for comparative differential expression analysis (7). Biomarker candidates are identified by Cuffdiff from FDR correcting the p-values associated with the test-statistic of means tests of each conditions distribution expression values for each gene . Tailor provides a set of secondary analysis tools that produce visually digestible summations of the salient features common among the samples of a particular phenotype. Tailors analysis workflow enables biologists to extract RNA in a noninvasive manner from blood or urine and identify the causal genetic phenomena associated with the presentation of a diseased phenotype.

Results/Summary of the Investigation:

In a recent comparative analysis between 9 males diagnosed with non-cancerous, fibrosis-associated, lower urinary tract syndrome (LUTS) and 9 canonically healthy males serving as a control group, Tailor analyzed ~1 Tb of RNA-Seq data over the course of 31 hours. The samples were provided by 9 males diagnosed with non-cancerous fibrosis-associated lower urinary tract syndrome and 9 males serving as an archetypal control group. RNA was extracted, ligated with sample-specific adapters, and multiplexed to reduce flow-cell lane bias. The Tailor pipeline workflow began with a demultiplexing step and then proceeded to a quality control step with FastQC. before trimming of the sample-specific adapters. At this point in the pipeline, sequence library preparation has completed and the reads are mapped to a reference genome/transcriptome. Tailor performed alignment to the hg38 Homo sapiens reference genome with the Tophat tool-suite yielding an average overall unique mapping rate of 94.0% with a minimum overall mapping rate of 82.3%. Average concordant pair-mapping rate to the hg38 genome was 82.2% with a minimum per-sample concordant pair-mapping rate of 66.8%. Tailor assembled transcripts for 32245 genes, 92397 isoforms, 54249 coding sequences. Tailor detected sufficient expression levels to determine statistical significance during differential expression analysis for 25171 coding sequences, 15118 genes, 32316 isoforms. Of the features with adequate expression levels, 115 coding sequences, 370 genes, and 251 isoforms were identified as significantly differentially expressed. Leave-one-out cross validation produced 18 sets of significantly differentially expressed genes with similar totals for the significant differential expression of sed gene set from each iteration. The average total number of significantly differentially expressed genes was 225. Cross-validation whittled the final high-confidence biomarker set down to 27 genes that were consistently differentially expressed independent from the influences of single samples. Gene ontology analysis identified significant enrichment for 33 molecular functions, 34 cellular components, and 102 biological processes between the groups.

Extended Analysis Section:

In order to remove any spurious calls that Tailor may have produced, a second differential expression analysis was performed. Performing repeated analyses with other commonly used software packages provides the added benefit of an accuracy quantification estimate for Tailors biomarker calls. The additional in silico prediction refinement analysis is being performed in the R statistical programming environment with several other Bioconductor packages for differential expression analysis (8). Raw read counts extracted from Tailors SQLite database backend will serve as input for EdgeR and Limma (9,10). Features that are consistently identified by each of the analysis methods will be interpreted as true positives. Features that are not consistently identified by each method will be interpreted as spurious calls and omitted from the final biomarker set. The final set of biomarker features will be in-vivo validated by either nanoDrop sequencing or qtPCR to determine their efficacy as a test for new patients suffereing from the disease.

Filtering and Normalizing Gene Expression Values

While RNA-Sequencing is less biased method than microarray, there are several sources of noise that must be filetered from the data. Lane biases in the flowcell can be mitigated through multiplexing but differences in sequencing depth require scaling the sizes of the libraries. Additionally, longer genes which produce more reads per transcript than smaller genes, require additional normalization from raw read counts to FPKM values. This conversion normalizes counts by the fragments per kilobase (gene length) per million mapped reads (genome length). Genes that were not expressed at a biologically meaningful level in either condition were filtered to reduce the number of unproductive differential expression tests carried out downstream. A minimum of at least 1 count per million mapped reads in at least \(1/4\) of the samples was set as the thresh-hold to characterize a gene as expressed. Genes that were expressed below this threshold were characterized as unexpressed. Filtered gene expression counts were then analyzed with EdgeR and Limma, two commonly used Bioconductor packages for differential expression analysis (9, 10).

Limma Linear Models

Limma was used to fit a linear model for each gene that modeled the gene expression of the control group as the predictor variable and the gene expression of the luts patient group as the response variable. A Shapiro-Wilks test of the data demonstrates that gene expression values is not normally distributed and therefor is not feasibly modeled with an ordinary least squares (OLS) regression. The count data additionally exhibits heteroscedascity of the variance that is not independent of the mean. To accommodate this mean-variance relationship a negative binomial distribution was used to model the count data assumes a quadratic relationship between the mean variance. This relationship results from a combination of technical variation in the sequencing experiment and biological variation amongst the replicated samples from each group. The count data is modeled with the voom Bioconductor package as a negative binomial distribution with the precision weights being easily calculated the voom normalization command. The voom output demonstrates a reduction in the trend between the means and variances. However there is a problematic trend between the models residual variances and the average expression values. To eliminate this relationship empirical Bayes moderation is performed by estimating gene-wise variability across the entire dataset. The qqplot of the moderated t-statistic suggests that the model fit is apppropriate.

Interpretation/Conclusion of the Investigation:

The 370 genes that Tailor identified as significantly differentially expressed will serve as biomarker candidates for the next analysis phase. Of the biomarker candidates, the 27 genes identified by Tailor as consistently significantly differentially expressed are considered to be the highest confidence biomarker candidates. In vivo verification of the biomarker candidates is currently being planned with nanoDrop sequencing a far less sensitive technology. The results of nanoDrop sequencing RNA extracted from the exact same urine samples will elucidate the accuracy of the Tailor pipeline for biomarker discovery and disease testing. If in vivo verification produces results consistent with those of the Tailor pipeline, then it is possible that nanoDrop sequencing of urine specimens may become a low-cost and non-invasive diagnostic for the detection of fibrosis-associated lower urinary tract syndrome. Tailor is being prepared for release as an open-source tool-package available for academic research due to the consistency of the preliminary results during perturbation. Tailors sensitivity to the unique gene expression profiles associated with RNA extracted from urine provide a level of precision that is uncommon amongst currently available workflows. A second release of the Tailor pipeline is being planned in order to incorporate a variant/SNP analysis as well.
